// Peoples profiles — biblical + ANE context (Cush, etc.)
// Extracted from SWRV_Genesis_Study monolith.

window.PEOPLES = {"Cush":{"altName":"Kush, Chus","biblical":"Son of Ham (Gen 10:6); first named son of Ham. Father of Nimrod (10:8). Ancestor of the Cushite peoples.","region":"Lands south of Egypt — Nubia, modern-day Sudan and Ethiopia, parts of southern Arabia. The Hebrew Bible uses 'Cush' interchangeably with what Greek translators called 'Ethiopia.'","appearance":"Dark brown to black skin. Sub-Saharan African and Nubian features. Jeremiah 13:23 directly references this — 'Can the Cushite (Ethiopian) change his skin?' — the rhetorical force only works if their skin is visibly distinct. Egyptian tomb paintings at Beni Hasan, Karnak, and elsewhere consistently depict Cushites with very dark skin distinct from Egyptians.","diet":"Cattle (their wealth), sorghum and millet (staple grains), fish from the Nile, dates, beer, wild game","notable":"Nimrod (Gen 10:8-12) — first 'mighty man' (gibbor) and empire-builder. The Queen of Sheba's region was likely Cushite or nearby.","sources":"Genesis 10:6-8; Jeremiah 13:23; Numbers 12:1 (Moses' Cushite wife); Josephus Antiquities I.6.2 — 'time has not at all hurt the name of Chus; for the Ethiopians, over whom he reigned, are even at this day, both by themselves and by all men in Asia, called Chusites.'"},"Mizraim":{"altName":"Egypt","biblical":"Son of Ham (Gen 10:6); the Hebrew word for Egypt itself. The dual ending '-ayim' refers to Upper and Lower Egypt.","region":"Nile Valley — from the Delta in the north to Aswan in the south. Among the most fertile and powerful civilizations of the ancient world.","appearance":"Egyptian art self-depicts as red-brown to dark brown skinned. North African / Mediterranean features blended with sub-Saharan elements — particularly in Upper Egypt closer to Cush. They distinguished themselves from both lighter Asiatics (the Levant) and darker Cushites in their tomb paintings, but were themselves clearly NOT pale.","diet":"Bread (emmer wheat), beer (the daily staple drink), fish, geese, lotus seeds, dates, figs, onions, garlic. Beef and lamb on feast days. The poor lived on bread, beer, and onions.","notable":"Pharaoh dynasties; the Ten Plagues; Joseph's adopted homeland","sources":"Genesis 10:6,13-14; Genesis 12:10-20; Genesis 39-50; Josephus Antiquities I.6.2; Egyptian self-representation in tomb art at Saqqara, Thebes, and Karnak"},"Phut":{"altName":"Put, Libyans","biblical":"Son of Ham (Gen 10:6). Often paired with Cush and Mizraim in prophetic oracles.","region":"Libya — North Africa west of Egypt","appearance":"Brown skin; Berber/North African features. Egyptian art depicts Libyans with lighter skin than Cushites but darker than Asiatics, with distinctive feathered headwear and beards.","sources":"Genesis 10:6; Ezekiel 27:10, 30:5, 38:5 (Phut as mercenaries); Jeremiah 46:9; Josephus Antiquities I.6.2"},"Canaan":{"altName":"Canaanites","biblical":"Son of Ham (Gen 10:6); cursed by Noah (Gen 9:25-27). His descendants populated the Levant — the land later promised to Abraham.","region":"The Levant — modern Israel, Lebanon, western Syria, western Jordan. The land between the Mediterranean and the Jordan River, north into the mountains of Lebanon.","appearance":"Olive-brown to brown skin; Mediterranean Semitic features. Indistinguishable in appearance from the Hebrews who would later inhabit the same land — they were ethnically and culturally similar Semites.","diet":"Wheat, barley, olives and olive oil, figs, grapes/wine, dates, pomegranates, dairy (yogurt, cheese), lamb/goat, fish on the coast","notable":"Sodom, Gomorrah, Hebron, Salem (Jerusalem), Shechem — all Canaanite cities the patriarchs interacted with","sources":"Genesis 10:6,15-19; Genesis 9:25-27; Genesis 12:6 ('the Canaanite was then in the land'); Josephus Antiquities I.6.2"},"Shem":{"altName":"Sem; ancestor of the Semitic peoples","biblical":"Eldest son of Noah (Gen 10:21-31). Ancestor of the Hebrews, Arabs, Aramaeans, Assyrians, and other Semitic peoples through Eber, Asshur, and Aram.","region":"Mesopotamia (Asshur), Arabia, Aram (Syria), and Elam stretching to Persia. The middle band of the ancient world.","appearance":"Olive to brown skin; black hair; Levantine/Mesopotamian Semitic features. Average height ~5'5\" for men based on archaeological remains. Beards and long hair were standard.","diet":"Bread, dairy, dates, lamb/goat for special occasions, lentils, olives in the western range","notable":"Through Shem comes Eber (root of 'Hebrew'), then Abraham, Isaac, Jacob, and the entire Israelite nation","sources":"Genesis 5:32, 10:21-31, 11:10-26; Josephus Antiquities I.6.4 — 'Shem, the third son of Noah, had five sons, who inhabited the land that began at Euphrates, and reached to the Indian Ocean.'"},"Japheth":{"altName":"Iapetus (in Greek tradition)","biblical":"Son of Noah (Gen 10:2-5). 'God shall enlarge Japheth, and he shall dwell in the tents of Shem' (Gen 9:27).","region":"Anatolia (Turkey), Greek isles, Iran, the Caucasus, southern Russia. The northern band of the ancient world.","appearance":"Lighter skin tones — Mediterranean to fair. Mixed features ranging from Greek/Anatolian to Iranian to northern European among the diverse descendants.","notable":"Javan (Greeks/Ionians), Madai (Medes), Tubal and Meshech (Anatolian peoples), Gomer (Cimmerians)","sources":"Genesis 10:2-5; Josephus Antiquities I.6.1 — identifies Japheth's descendants with Greeks, Medes, Iberians, and 'all those nations beyond the Black Sea.'"},"Abraham":{"altName":"Abram","biblical":"Son of Terah, descended from Shem through Eber. Born in Ur of the Chaldees. Called by YHWH at age 75 (Gen 12). Father of Ishmael (by Hagar) and Isaac (by Sarah).","region":"Born in Ur (southern Mesopotamia, modern Iraq). Migrated to Haran (northern Mesopotamia, modern Turkey/Syria border), then to Canaan.","appearance":"Semitic features — olive-brown skin, black hair, beard. Mesopotamian-Levantine. The biblical text never describes him in racial terms — but his origin (Mesopotamia) and his descendants' settlement (Levant) place him squarely in the Semitic phenotype range. NOT European — that interpretive tradition is anachronistic.","diet":"Semi-nomadic patriarch — bread, milk and curds (Gen 18:8), meat from his own flocks for guests, wine, olives, figs","notable":"Friend of God (Isa 41:8); father of faith (Rom 4); friend to the Pharaoh of Egypt (Gen 12), to Abimelech of Gerar (Gen 20-21), and to the Canaanite kings (Gen 14)","sources":"Genesis 11:26-25:11; Joshua 24:2-3; Josephus Antiquities I.7-17"},"Hagar":{"altName":"-","biblical":"Egyptian handmaid of Sarai (Gen 16). Mother of Ishmael by Abraham. The first person in Scripture to give God a name — El Roi, 'the God who sees me' (Gen 16:13).","region":"Egyptian — likely brought into Sarah's household during their stay in Egypt (Gen 12:10-20). Settled with Ishmael in the wilderness of Paran (Gen 21:21).","appearance":"Egyptian — red-brown to brown skin, dark hair, North African features. Visually distinct from her Semitic mistress Sarah.","sources":"Genesis 16, 21; Josephus Antiquities I.10"},"Ishmael":{"altName":"-","biblical":"Firstborn son of Abraham, by Hagar the Egyptian. Father of 12 princes (Gen 25:13-16); ancestor of the Arab peoples.","region":"Wilderness of Paran (northern Arabian peninsula). His descendants spread across Arabia.","appearance":"MIXED Semitic-Egyptian heritage — half Hebrew (Abraham), half Egyptian (Hagar). Brown skin in the Arabian range. Tall stature ('a wild man… his hand against every man,' Gen 16:12) — recognized as a warrior people.","notable":"Founding father of the Arabs by Hebrew tradition. Buried his father Abraham alongside Isaac (Gen 25:9) — the brothers reconciled at the grave.","sources":"Genesis 16, 17, 21, 25; Josephus Antiquities I.12 — 'his sons inhabited that country which extends from Euphrates to the Red Sea, and called it Nabatene.'"},"Asenath":{"altName":"-","biblical":"Egyptian wife of Joseph, daughter of Potiphera priest of On (Gen 41:45). Mother of Manasseh and Ephraim — the two tribes carrying Joseph's blessing into Israel.","region":"Egyptian — from On (Heliopolis, the Egyptian sun-cult center)","appearance":"Egyptian — red-brown skin, dark hair, Egyptian features. The mothers of two of Israel's twelve tribes (Manasseh, Ephraim) were therefore HALF EGYPTIAN — meaning two of the founding tribes of Israel had visible African ancestry.","sources":"Genesis 41:45,50-52; Genesis 46:20"},"Tamar":{"altName":"-","biblical":"Canaanite daughter-in-law of Judah (Gen 38). Mother of Perez and Zerah by Judah. Ancestress of David and of Christ (Matthew 1:3).","region":"Canaanite","appearance":"Canaanite Semitic — olive-brown skin","notable":"In the Messianic line. Her story is one of survival under levirate-marriage failure. Listed by Matthew among Christ's four named female ancestors (along with Rahab, Ruth, Bathsheba) — three of whom were non-Israelite.","sources":"Genesis 38; Ruth 4:12; Matthew 1:3"},"Rebekah":{"altName":"-","biblical":"Wife of Isaac. Daughter of Bethuel (Aramean). Mother of Esau and Jacob.","region":"Padan-Aram (northern Mesopotamia, near Haran)","appearance":"Aramean Semitic — same general appearance as Abraham's family. The text emphasizes Isaac sought a wife from his OWN PEOPLE, not from the Canaanites. Same Semitic phenotype.","sources":"Genesis 24, 25, 27"},"Rachel":{"altName":"-","biblical":"Daughter of Laban (Aramean). Younger wife of Jacob. Mother of Joseph and Benjamin.","region":"Padan-Aram","appearance":"Aramean Semitic — described as 'beautiful in form and face' (Gen 29:17). Darker complexion than her sister Leah's lighter eyes (the Hebrew rakkot can mean weak/tender or lovely).","sources":"Genesis 29-35"},"Leah":{"altName":"-","biblical":"Daughter of Laban. Older sister of Rachel. First wife of Jacob (by deception). Mother of Reuben, Simeon, Levi, Judah, Issachar, Zebulun, and Dinah.","region":"Padan-Aram","appearance":"Aramean Semitic. Hebrew describes her eyes as 'rakkot' — translated 'tender,' 'weak,' or 'lovely' depending on interpretation. From Leah comes Levi (priesthood) and Judah (kingship) — the two foundational tribes.","sources":"Genesis 29-35, 49"},"Joseph":{"altName":"-","biblical":"Son of Jacob and Rachel. Sold into Egyptian slavery; rose to become vice-regent of Egypt. Father of Manasseh and Ephraim by Asenath.","region":"Born in Padan-Aram; raised in Canaan; lived from age 17 in Egypt.","appearance":"Hebrew Semitic by birth — but blended visually into Egyptian society once dressed in Egyptian fashion. His brothers did NOT recognize him at his Egyptian court (Gen 42:8) — likely a combination of his Egyptian dress, Egyptian-style shaved face (Egyptian custom, Gen 41:14), royal regalia, and the linguistic interpreter he used (Gen 42:23). His children with Asenath were half-Egyptian.","diet":"As an Egyptian governor, he ate Egyptian food. The Egyptians 'might not eat bread with the Hebrews; for that is an abomination unto the Egyptians' (Gen 43:32) — Egyptian food taboos kept them ritually separated.","sources":"Genesis 37, 39-50; Josephus Antiquities II.2-8"},"Moabites":{"altName":"-","biblical":"Descendants of Lot through his elder daughter (Gen 19:37). Settled east of the Dead Sea.","region":"East of the Dead Sea, modern-day Jordan","appearance":"Semitic — same general appearance as Hebrews and Canaanites","notable":"Ruth was a Moabitess; ancestress of David and Christ.","sources":"Genesis 19:30-38; Ruth"},"Ammonites":{"altName":"Bene-Ammon","biblical":"Descendants of Lot through his younger daughter (Gen 19:38). Settled east of the Jordan, north of Moab.","region":"Trans-Jordan, around modern Amman","appearance":"Semitic — same general phenotype","sources":"Genesis 19:30-38"},
  "Moses": {"altName": "Mosheh (Hebrew)", "biblical": "Born to Hebrew slave parents Amram and Jochebed during Pharaoh's edict to kill Hebrew sons (Exod 2). Raised in Pharaoh's house. Called by God at the burning bush (Exod 3). Led Israel out of Egypt and through 40 years in the wilderness. Received the Torah on Sinai. Author of the Pentateuch.", "region": "Born in Egypt, raised in Pharaoh's court, exiled to Midian (NW Arabia), led Israel through Sinai and Transjordan. Died on Mount Nebo overlooking the Promised Land.", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic Hebrew man. Egyptian-raised meant his presentation was Egyptian — clean-shaven (Egyptian custom), in linen, fluent in Egyptian language. Brown skin, dark eyes, dark hair. His sister Miriam was visibly Semitic; his wife Zipporah was Cushite (Num 12:1).", "diet": "Royal Egyptian fare in his first 40 years (bread, beer, beef, fish, vegetables, fruit). In Midian and the wilderness: shepherd's food — bread, cheese, dates, water, occasional meat. In the wilderness, ate the manna with Israel for 40 years.", "notable": "Spoke face-to-face with God 'as a man speaks to his friend' (Exod 33:11). Wrote the Torah. Greatest prophet in Israel's history until Jesus. Numbers 12:3 — 'Now the man Moses was very meek, above all the men which were upon the face of the earth.'", "sources": "Exodus 2-Deuteronomy 34; Josephus Antiquities II.9-IV.8; Strong's H4872."},
  "Aaron": {"altName": "Aharon (Hebrew)", "biblical": "Older brother of Moses, son of Amram and Jochebed (Exod 6:20). Israel's first high priest. Spoke for Moses before Pharaoh. Made the golden calf (Exod 32) — major moral failure. Died on Mount Hor before Israel entered Canaan.", "region": "Born and raised in Egypt; served as priest through the wilderness journey.", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic Hebrew. Wore the elaborate priestly garments described in Exodus 28 — ephod, breastplate with 12 stones, turban, bells and pomegranates on the hem.", "diet": "Priests' portions of the sacrifices: meat from peace offerings, grain offerings (except memorial portion), bread of the Presence. Strict prohibitions: no wine when serving (Lev 10:9).", "notable": "Founder of the Aaronic priesthood. His staff budded miraculously (Num 17). His golden calf incident is one of Israel's darkest moments; his sons Nadab and Abihu were killed for offering strange fire (Lev 10).", "sources": "Exodus-Numbers; Leviticus 8-10 (consecration); Strong's H175."},
  "Miriam": {"altName": "Miryam (Hebrew)", "biblical": "Older sister of Moses and Aaron (Num 26:59). Watched over baby Moses at the Nile (Exod 2:4-8). Led Israel's women in song after the Red Sea crossing (Exod 15:20-21). A prophetess. Struck with leprosy for opposing Moses (Num 12). Died at Kadesh.", "region": "Born in Egypt, lived through the wilderness journey.", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic Hebrew woman. Older than Moses by perhaps a decade.", "diet": "Hebrew slave food in Egypt; manna and the simple desert diet through the wilderness.", "notable": "First woman explicitly called a prophetess in scripture (Exod 15:20). Her song at the Red Sea may be one of the oldest fragments of Hebrew poetry preserved in the Bible.", "sources": "Exodus 15; Numbers 12, 20:1; Micah 6:4; Strong's H4813."},
  "Joshua": {"altName": "Yehoshua (Hebrew) — 'YHWH saves'; same root as 'Jesus'", "biblical": "Son of Nun, of the tribe of Ephraim. Moses' military commander and successor. Led Israel across the Jordan and conquered Canaan. The book of Joshua is named for him.", "region": "Born in Egypt during the slavery; led Israel into and across Canaan.", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic Hebrew. Warrior-leader.", "diet": "Wilderness manna for 40 years; in Canaan, transitioned to Canaanite agricultural produce (Josh 5:11-12 — manna ceased the day they ate of the produce of the land).", "notable": "Said 'as for me and my house, we will serve the LORD' (Josh 24:15). Lived to 110. The sun stood still over Gibeon during his battle (Josh 10).", "sources": "Numbers, Deuteronomy 31, Joshua 1-24; Strong's H3091."},
  "Caleb": {"altName": "Kalev (Hebrew) — 'wholehearted'", "biblical": "One of the 12 spies sent by Moses (Num 13). Only he and Joshua brought back a faithful report. Lived 45 years through the wilderness and into Canaan, still ready to fight at 85 (Josh 14:10-12). Received Hebron as his inheritance.", "region": "Of the tribe of Judah. Settled in Hebron in southern Canaan.", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic Hebrew. Note: Caleb's clan name 'Kenizzite' (Num 32:12) suggests his family had Edomite origins — adopted into Judah.", "diet": "Wilderness manna; Canaanite produce; lived as a southern hill-country farmer/herder.", "notable": "The Bible repeatedly says Caleb 'wholly followed the LORD' (Num 14:24, Josh 14:14). At 85 he said: 'Give me this mountain' — and conquered it.", "sources": "Numbers 13-14; Joshua 14-15; Strong's H3612."},
  "Rahab": {"altName": "Rachav (Hebrew)", "biblical": "Canaanite prostitute of Jericho who hid the two Israelite spies (Josh 2). Her family was spared when Jericho fell. Listed in Matthew 1:5 as ancestor of David and of Jesus. Praised in Hebrews 11:31 and James 2:25 as an example of faith.", "region": "Jericho, in Canaan. After its fall, joined Israel; settled likely near Bethlehem (married Salmon).", "appearance": "Canaanite woman — Afro-Asiatic Semitic background, brown skin, dark features, similar to neighboring Hebrews.", "diet": "Canaanite urban diet: bread, oil, wine, dates, figs, sheep and goat meat, fish from the Jordan.", "notable": "A Gentile prostitute is named in Jesus' genealogy (Matt 1:5). Her faith confessed: 'YHWH your God, he is God in heaven above, and in earth beneath' (Josh 2:11).", "sources": "Joshua 2, 6; Matthew 1:5; Hebrews 11:31; James 2:25; Strong's H7343."},
  "Ruth": {"altName": "Ruth (Hebrew)", "biblical": "Moabite widow who refused to leave her Israelite mother-in-law Naomi: 'whither thou goest, I will go' (Ruth 1:16). Married Boaz. Great-grandmother of King David. Listed in Matthew 1:5 as ancestor of Jesus.", "region": "Born in Moab (east of the Dead Sea); migrated to Bethlehem with Naomi.", "appearance": "Moabite woman — Afro-Asiatic Semitic, brown skin, dark features. Moabites descended from Lot (Gen 19:36-37), so physically similar to Hebrews.", "diet": "Moabite agricultural diet (similar to Canaanite). In Bethlehem, gleaning in the barley and wheat fields.", "notable": "A foreign widow becomes the great-grandmother of King David and ancestor of the Messiah. One of only five women named in Jesus' genealogy.", "sources": "Ruth 1-4; Matthew 1:5; Strong's H7327."},
  "Boaz": {"altName": "Boaz — 'in him is strength'", "biblical": "Wealthy landowner of Bethlehem who married Ruth the Moabite under the kinsman-redeemer law (Ruth 4). Great-grandfather of King David.", "region": "Bethlehem of Judah.", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic Hebrew of the tribe of Judah.", "diet": "Prosperous Israelite agricultural diet — bread, meat, wine, olive oil, vegetables, fruit.", "notable": "His name was used for one of the two pillars at the entrance to Solomon's Temple (1 Kgs 7:21). Christ-figure — the kinsman-redeemer who lifts up the foreign widow.", "sources": "Ruth 2-4; 1 Chronicles 2:11-12; Matthew 1:5; Strong's H1162."},
  "Samuel": {"altName": "Shmuel (Hebrew) — 'heard of God'", "biblical": "Son of Hannah, miraculous answer to her prayer (1 Sam 1). Last judge of Israel and first of the great prophets. Anointed Saul and then David as kings of Israel.", "region": "Born in the hill country of Ephraim; ministered at Shiloh, Ramah, and circuit cities.", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic Hebrew. Wore a linen ephod from childhood (1 Sam 2:18).", "diet": "Priestly portions and prophetic simplicity.", "notable": "Heard God's voice as a child (1 Sam 3). Mourned for Saul. Recognized David though he was the least likely son. The bridge between the era of judges and the era of kings.", "sources": "1 Samuel 1-25; Acts 13:20; Hebrews 11:32; Strong's H8050."},
  "Saul": {"altName": "Shaul (Hebrew) — 'asked for'", "biblical": "Son of Kish, of the tribe of Benjamin. Israel's first king. Tall, handsome, anointed by Samuel (1 Sam 9-10). Disobeyed God, was rejected, declined into paranoia and tried to kill David. Died by suicide at Mount Gilboa (1 Sam 31).", "region": "From Gibeah of Benjamin in central Canaan. Reigned over a still-tribal Israel.", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic Hebrew. Described as 'a choice young man, and a goodly' — head and shoulders taller than any of the people (1 Sam 9:2). The most physically striking man in Israel.", "diet": "Royal Israelite fare — but Israel's royalty was still simple compared to surrounding empires.", "notable": "Tragic figure — the king the people demanded, the king God reluctantly gave them. His decline from anointed deliverer to paranoid hunter of David is one of the Bible's saddest arcs.", "sources": "1 Samuel 9-31; Acts 13:21; Strong's H7586."},
  "David": {"altName": "Dawid (Hebrew) — 'beloved'", "biblical": "Youngest son of Jesse of Bethlehem. Anointed by Samuel as a youth (1 Sam 16). Killed Goliath. Served Saul, then fled from him. Reigned over Judah at Hebron, then over all Israel at Jerusalem. 'A man after God's own heart' (1 Sam 13:14, Acts 13:22). Author of many Psalms.", "region": "Born in Bethlehem of Judah; established his capital at Jerusalem; reigned over all Israel from Dan to Beersheba.", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic Hebrew. 1 Samuel 16:12 — 'he was ruddy, and withal of a beautiful countenance, and goodly to look to.' 'Ruddy' (adamoni) in a brown-skinned Semitic context likely meant healthy/reddish-brown complexion. Probably medium height (compared to Saul's notable tallness).", "diet": "Shepherd's food as a boy; royal fare as king (1 Chr 12:39-40 lists provisions sent to David: bread, meal, figs, raisins, wine, oil, oxen, sheep).", "notable": "Killed Goliath with a sling. Played the harp. Wrote about half the Psalms. Took Bathsheba and arranged Uriah's death — the great moral fall of his life. Father of Solomon. Ancestor of Jesus 'the Son of David.'", "sources": "1 Samuel 16 - 1 Kings 2; 1 Chronicles 10-29; Psalms; Matthew 1:1; Strong's H1732."},
  "Jonathan": {"altName": "Yehonatan (Hebrew) — 'YHWH gave'", "biblical": "Saul's eldest son. Crown prince of Israel. Made a covenant of love with David (1 Sam 18:1-4). Repeatedly saved David from his father's wrath. Killed alongside Saul at Mount Gilboa (1 Sam 31).", "region": "Lived in Gibeah of Benjamin; fought across Israel.", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic Hebrew. Mighty warrior.", "diet": "Royal Israelite fare.", "notable": "His soul was 'knit to the soul of David' (1 Sam 18:1). One of the great friendships in scripture. David's lament for him: 'thy love to me was wonderful, passing the love of women' (2 Sam 1:26).", "sources": "1 Samuel 13-31; 2 Samuel 1; Strong's H3083."},
  "Bathsheba": {"altName": "Bat-sheva (Hebrew) — 'daughter of seven/oath'", "biblical": "Wife of Uriah the Hittite. Seen bathing by David, who took her and arranged Uriah's death (2 Sam 11). Their first son died. Their second son was Solomon. Listed (unnamed) in Matthew 1:6 in Jesus' genealogy.", "region": "Jerusalem.", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic Hebrew woman (her husband was Hittite, but Bathsheba's lineage was Israelite — daughter of Eliam, granddaughter of David's counselor Ahithophel).", "diet": "Wife of a soldier, then queen — both Israelite urban fare.", "notable": "Mother of Solomon. Mother of Nathan. Listed in Jesus' genealogy as 'her that had been the wife of Urias.' Her son Solomon became Israel's wisest king.", "sources": "2 Samuel 11-12; 1 Kings 1-2; Matthew 1:6; Strong's H1339."},
  "Solomon": {"altName": "Shlomoh (Hebrew) — 'his peace'", "biblical": "Son of David and Bathsheba. Third king of Israel. Built the First Temple in Jerusalem. Famed for wisdom — 1 Kgs 3 records his prayer for a 'hearing heart' and God's reply. Wrote Proverbs, Ecclesiastes, Song of Songs. Married 700 wives and 300 concubines (1 Kgs 11). Drifted into idolatry late in life.", "region": "Jerusalem. His kingdom extended from the Euphrates to the border of Egypt (1 Kgs 4:21).", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic Hebrew of the line of David.", "diet": "Lavish royal table — 1 Kgs 4:22-23 records his daily provision: 30 measures of fine flour, 60 measures of meal, 10 fatted oxen, 20 pasture oxen, 100 sheep, deer, gazelles, roebucks, fowl.", "notable": "Built the Temple (1 Kgs 6). Visited by the Queen of Sheba. Famous worldwide for wisdom. But his many foreign wives turned his heart from YHWH (1 Kgs 11:1-8) — the seed of Israel's eventual division.", "sources": "2 Samuel 12 - 1 Kings 11; 1 Chronicles 28-29 - 2 Chronicles 9; Proverbs, Ecclesiastes, Song of Songs; Matthew 1:6; Strong's H8010."},
  "Elijah": {"altName": "Eliyahu (Hebrew) — 'my God is YHWH'", "biblical": "Tishbite prophet of Gilead. Active during the reigns of Ahab and Ahaziah in the Northern Kingdom (~870 BC). Confronted Baal worship. Mount Carmel showdown with 450 prophets of Baal (1 Kgs 18). Taken up to heaven in a whirlwind (2 Kgs 2). Appeared with Moses at the Transfiguration (Matt 17).", "region": "Gilead (east of the Jordan); ministered throughout the Northern Kingdom.", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic Hebrew. Wore a hairy mantle and a leather belt (2 Kgs 1:8) — the distinctive prophetic garb later copied by John the Baptist (Matt 3:4).", "diet": "Fed by ravens (1 Kgs 17:6). Sustained by the widow of Zarephath's miraculous oil and meal. Fed by an angel under the broom tree (1 Kgs 19:6).", "notable": "Never died — taken to heaven alive. Expected to return before the great day of the LORD (Mal 4:5). His mantle fell on Elisha (2 Kgs 2:13).", "sources": "1 Kings 17-21; 2 Kings 1-2; Malachi 4:5; Matthew 17:1-13; James 5:17; Strong's H452."},
  "Elisha": {"altName": "Elisha (Hebrew) — 'God is salvation'", "biblical": "Elijah's successor. Asked for a 'double portion' of Elijah's spirit (2 Kgs 2:9). Performed twice as many recorded miracles as Elijah. Healed Naaman, raised the Shunammite's son, multiplied loaves, and at the height of crisis prayed for his servant to see the chariots of fire (2 Kgs 6:17).", "region": "Northern Kingdom; based at Mount Carmel and Samaria; traveled to Jericho, Shunem, Damascus.", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic Hebrew. Bald — children mocked him for it (2 Kgs 2:23).", "diet": "Itinerant prophetic life; sustained by his community (the 'sons of the prophets') and by direct miracles.", "notable": "Even after his death, his bones raised a man from the dead (2 Kgs 13:21). The fullest prophet-miracle catalog in the OT.", "sources": "1 Kings 19:16-21; 2 Kings 2-13; Strong's H477."},
  "Isaiah": {"altName": "Yesha'yahu (Hebrew) — 'YHWH saves'", "biblical": "Prophet to Judah ~740-680 BC. Prophesied during the reigns of Uzziah, Jotham, Ahaz, and Hezekiah. Saw YHWH on his throne in Isaiah 6. Predicted the virgin birth (Isa 7:14), the Suffering Servant (Isa 53), and the new heavens and new earth (Isa 65-66).", "region": "Jerusalem and the kingdom of Judah.", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic Hebrew. Walked barefoot and naked for three years as a sign-act (Isa 20).", "diet": "Standard Jerusalem fare; had access to the king's court.", "notable": "The most-quoted OT prophet in the New Testament. Saw the throne vision that defined Jewish mystical tradition. According to Jewish tradition (Martyrdom of Isaiah; alluded to in Heb 11:37), he was 'sawn asunder' under King Manasseh.", "sources": "Isaiah 1-66; 2 Kings 19-20; 2 Chronicles 26-32; Hebrews 11:37; Strong's H3470."},
  "Jeremiah": {"altName": "Yirmeyahu (Hebrew) — 'YHWH lifts up'", "biblical": "Prophet during Judah's final 40 years (~626-586 BC). Born in Anathoth of priestly family. Called from the womb (Jer 1:5). Witnessed Jerusalem's fall to Babylon. Author of Lamentations. Known as the 'weeping prophet.'", "region": "Anathoth and Jerusalem; later taken to Egypt against his will.", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic Hebrew.", "diet": "Suffered scarcity during the Babylonian siege; sustained miraculously by Ebed-melech the Cushite who pulled him from the cistern (Jer 38).", "notable": "Wept for his people. Predicted the 70-year captivity (Jer 25:11). Bought a field as a sign of Israel's return (Jer 32). Promised the New Covenant (Jer 31:31-34) — quoted in Hebrews 8.", "sources": "Jeremiah 1-52; Lamentations; 2 Kings 24-25; 2 Chronicles 36; Strong's H3414."},
  "Ezekiel": {"altName": "Yechezkel (Hebrew) — 'God strengthens'", "biblical": "Priest-prophet exiled to Babylon in 597 BC. Received his throne vision by the river Chebar (Ezek 1). Acted out elaborate sign-acts (lying on his side, shaving his hair). Saw the valley of dry bones (Ezek 37) and the future Temple (Ezek 40-48).", "region": "Born in Judah, exiled to Tel-abib by the Chebar canal in Babylonia.", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic Hebrew priest.", "diet": "Exilic Jewish diet in Babylonia; performed elaborate sign-acts including eating bread cooked over dung (Ezek 4).", "notable": "Saw the chariot-throne vision that became the center of Jewish mysticism. Watched the glory of God depart from the Jerusalem temple (Ezek 10) and saw it return (Ezek 43).", "sources": "Ezekiel 1-48; Strong's H3168."},
  "Daniel": {"altName": "Daniyyel (Hebrew) — 'God is my judge'; Babylonian name: Belteshazzar", "biblical": "Taken to Babylon as a youth in 605 BC. Refused the king's food (Dan 1). Interpreted dreams for Nebuchadnezzar. Survived the lions' den under Darius. Received apocalyptic visions of the four kingdoms and the 70 weeks.", "region": "Born in Judah, served in the Babylonian and Persian courts.", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic Hebrew. Trained in Babylonian language, literature, and lore. Wore Babylonian/Persian court attire.", "diet": "Refused the king's meat and wine; ate vegetables and water (Dan 1:12) — yet grew healthier than his peers.", "notable": "Lived through the entire 70-year exile. Served four kings: Nebuchadnezzar, Belshazzar, Darius, Cyrus. Predicted the rise and fall of Persia, Greece, and Rome (Dan 2, 7, 8, 11).", "sources": "Daniel 1-12; Ezekiel 14:14; Strong's H1840."},
  "Mary": {"altName": "Miryam (Hebrew, Aramaic) — same name as Moses' sister", "biblical": "Young virgin of Nazareth in Galilee. Visited by the angel Gabriel (Luke 1:26-38). Bore Jesus the Messiah. Wife of Joseph the carpenter. Present at the Cross (John 19:25). Present at Pentecost (Acts 1:14).", "region": "Nazareth in Galilee. Traveled to Bethlehem for Jesus' birth; fled to Egypt to escape Herod; returned to Nazareth; followed Jesus' ministry.", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic Jewish woman of the first century. Brown skin, dark hair, dark eyes — the standard appearance of Galilean Jews of her era. Probably teenager when she conceived.", "diet": "Galilean village diet — bread, fish, olive oil, lentils, dates, figs, milk products, occasional meat.", "notable": "Said 'Behold the handmaid of the Lord; be it unto me according to thy word' (Luke 1:38). Her Magnificat (Luke 1:46-55) is one of the great prayers of scripture. The only woman named in the Apostles' Creed.", "sources": "Matthew 1-2; Luke 1-2; John 2:1-12, 19:25-27; Acts 1:14; Strong's G3137."},
  "Joseph_NT": {"altName": "Yosef (Hebrew); husband of Mary, foster-father of Jesus", "biblical": "Carpenter (tekton) of Nazareth, of the line of David. Espoused to Mary. Resolved to put her away quietly when she was found pregnant, but the angel reassured him in a dream (Matt 1). Took the family to Egypt to escape Herod's slaughter, then to Nazareth.", "region": "Nazareth in Galilee.", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic Jewish man. Working-class craftsman.", "diet": "Galilean village diet of a tradesman.", "notable": "Last mentioned in Luke 2:51 (when Jesus was 12). Tradition holds he died before Jesus' public ministry began. A quiet, just man who obeyed angelic warnings without recorded words in scripture.", "sources": "Matthew 1-2; Luke 1-2; Strong's G2501."},
  "Jesus": {"altName": "Yeshua (Hebrew/Aramaic) — same name as Joshua; means 'YHWH saves'. Greek: Iesous.", "biblical": "Son of Mary, conceived by the Holy Spirit. Born in Bethlehem (~6-4 BC). Grew up in Nazareth. Baptized by John in the Jordan ~AD 27. Preached the Kingdom of God for ~3 years. Crucified under Pontius Pilate at Passover ~AD 30-33. Raised on the third day. The Messiah of Israel.", "region": "Born in Bethlehem of Judea; raised in Nazareth of Galilee; ministered in Galilee, Judea, and across the Jordan; died and rose in Jerusalem.", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic Jewish man of the first century. Brown skin, dark hair, dark eyes — the standard appearance of Galilean Jews. The Bible does NOT describe his physical appearance. Isaiah 53:2 — 'he hath no form nor comeliness; and when we shall see him, there is no beauty that we should desire him' — meaning he looked ordinary, not striking. Revelation 1:14-15 describes the risen Christ with 'hairs as white as snow' and 'feet like unto fine brass, as if they burned in a furnace.'", "diet": "Galilean Jewish diet — bread, fish, olive oil, wine, dates, figs, lentils, lamb at Passover. Was accused of being 'a gluttonous man, and a winebibber' (Matt 11:19) because he ate freely with all kinds of people.", "notable": "The Messiah. The Word made flesh (John 1:14). The Lamb of God (John 1:29). The Resurrection and the Life (John 11:25). Coming again (Acts 1:11). Confessed throughout the NT as God incarnate, fully human, fully divine.", "sources": "Matthew, Mark, Luke, John; Acts 1; Josephus Antiquities XVIII.3.3 (Testimonium); all of the New Testament; Strong's G2424."},
  "JohnBaptist": {"altName": "Yochanan (Hebrew); John the Baptist", "biblical": "Son of the priest Zacharias and Elisabeth (a relative of Mary). Born about six months before Jesus. Lived in the wilderness. Preached repentance and baptized in the Jordan. Baptized Jesus. Killed by Herod Antipas for condemning Herod's marriage to Herodias (Matt 14, Mark 6).", "region": "Born in the hill country of Judea; ministered in the wilderness near the Jordan; killed at Machaerus (per Josephus).", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic Jewish man. Wore a camel's-hair garment with a leather belt (Matt 3:4) — deliberately echoing Elijah (2 Kgs 1:8).", "diet": "Locusts and wild honey (Matt 3:4). Took the Nazirite vow — no wine.", "notable": "Jesus called him 'more than a prophet' (Matt 11:9) and the greatest born of women (Matt 11:11). The forerunner of the Messiah. The voice in the wilderness (Isa 40:3). Confirmed by Josephus (Antiquities XVIII.5.2) as a historical figure of great influence.", "sources": "Matthew 3, 11, 14; Mark 1, 6; Luke 1, 3, 7; John 1, 3; Josephus Antiquities XVIII.5; Strong's G2491."},
  "Peter": {"altName": "Shimon Kefa (Aramaic) → Simon Peter → Petros (Greek, 'rock')", "biblical": "Galilean fisherman. Brother of Andrew. Called by Jesus (Matt 4:18-20). Confessed Jesus as the Christ (Matt 16:16). Denied Jesus three times. Restored by Jesus after the resurrection (John 21). Preached at Pentecost (Acts 2). Leader of the Jerusalem church. Traditionally martyred in Rome under Nero.", "region": "Bethsaida and Capernaum on the Sea of Galilee; later Jerusalem; tradition says Rome.", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic Galilean Jewish fisherman.", "diet": "Fisherman's diet — fish, bread, olive oil.", "notable": "Walked on water briefly (Matt 14:28-31). The 'rock' on which Jesus said he would build his church (Matt 16:18). Wrote 1 and 2 Peter. The first apostle to receive Gentiles into the church (Acts 10).", "sources": "Throughout the four Gospels; Acts 1-15; 1 and 2 Peter; Strong's G4074."},
  "Paul": {"altName": "Shaul (Hebrew) → Saul of Tarsus → Paulos (Greek, 'small'). Roman citizen.", "biblical": "Born in Tarsus (Asia Minor) to Jewish parents of the tribe of Benjamin. Pharisee, taught by Gamaliel. Persecuted the early church. Converted on the Damascus road (Acts 9). Apostle to the Gentiles. Made three missionary journeys. Wrote 13 epistles. Tradition holds he was beheaded in Rome under Nero around AD 67.", "region": "Born in Tarsus (modern Turkey); studied in Jerusalem; ministered throughout Asia Minor, Greece, and eventually Rome.", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic Jewish man, Roman citizen by birth. Possibly small in stature ('Paul' = 'small' in Latin). Had a 'thorn in the flesh' (2 Cor 12:7), often interpreted as a chronic physical condition.", "diet": "Mixed — Pharisaic kosher in youth, more flexible as apostle to Gentiles (1 Cor 9:19-23, 10:25-33).", "notable": "Wrote about half the books of the New Testament. Argued the gospel of grace through faith. Suffered shipwrecks, beatings, imprisonment, stoning. Confronted Peter at Antioch over Gentile inclusion (Gal 2). Greatest theologian of the early church.", "sources": "Acts 7-28; Romans through Philemon; 2 Peter 3:15-16; Strong's G3972."},
  "Pilate": {"altName": "Pontius Pilatus", "biblical": "Roman prefect of Judea AD 26-36. Tried Jesus and sentenced him to crucifixion despite finding 'no fault in this man' (Luke 23:4). Famously washed his hands of the verdict (Matt 27:24).", "region": "Roman prefect headquartered at Caesarea Maritima; came to Jerusalem for major Jewish festivals.", "appearance": "Roman official, likely of equestrian rank. Italian/Mediterranean ethnicity. Wore the toga of office; ruled from the Praetorium.", "diet": "Roman official's table — wine, olive oil, garum (fish sauce), bread, meats, fruits.", "notable": "Confirmed as a historical figure by Tacitus (Annals 15.44), by the Pilate Stone (1961 archaeological find at Caesarea), by Philo (Embassy to Gaius), and extensively by Josephus (Antiquities XVIII.3). Recalled to Rome for excessive brutality.", "sources": "All four Gospels; Acts 3:13, 4:27, 13:28; Josephus Antiquities XVIII.3-4; Tacitus Annals 15.44; Strong's G4091."},
  "Herod": {"altName": "Herod the Great", "biblical": "King of Judea 37-4 BC. Edomite (Idumean) by descent — a forced convert to Judaism. Built the Second Temple complex (the one Jesus knew). Slaughtered the innocents in Bethlehem trying to kill the infant Jesus (Matt 2).", "region": "Reigned from Jerusalem; massive building projects across Judea, Samaria, and Galilee.", "appearance": "Idumean (Edomite) origin — Afro-Asiatic Semitic, similar appearance to Jews of his time. Politically Hellenized; culturally Roman in his court.", "diet": "Royal Hellenistic-Roman table — extravagant by any standard.", "notable": "Built the Temple Mount platform, Caesarea Maritima harbor, Masada, the Herodium. Murdered his wife Mariamne, his mother-in-law, three of his sons, and many others. Augustus reportedly said it was 'better to be Herod's pig than his son' (he abstained from pork; he did not abstain from filicide). Documented extensively by Josephus.", "sources": "Matthew 2; Josephus Antiquities XIV-XVII; Strong's G2264."},
  "Caiaphas": {"altName": "Yosef Bar Kayafa", "biblical": "High priest of Israel AD 18-36. Presided over the trial of Jesus (Matt 26:57-68). Said it was 'expedient that one man should die for the people' (John 11:50, 18:14).", "region": "Jerusalem.", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic Jewish priest. Wore the High Priestly garments — ephod, breastplate, ornate robes.", "diet": "Aristocratic Sadducee diet — wealthy priestly family.", "notable": "Son-in-law of Annas the former high priest. The ossuary inscribed 'Yosef bar Kayafa' (found 1990 in Jerusalem) is widely accepted as belonging to this Caiaphas.", "sources": "Matthew 26; Luke 3:2; John 11, 18; Acts 4:6; Josephus Antiquities XVIII.2.2, XVIII.4.3; Strong's G2533."},
  "Adam": {"altName": "Adam (Hebrew) — 'man'; from adamah, 'ground/earth'", "biblical": "The first man, formed by God from the dust of the ground on the sixth day of creation (Gen 2:7). Placed in Eden to dress and keep it. Named the animals. Given Eve as a wife. Disobeyed God by eating from the tree of the knowledge of good and evil — bringing sin and death into creation (Rom 5:12). Lived 930 years.", "region": "Eden — somewhere east, by the four rivers Pison, Gihon, Hiddekel, and Euphrates.", "appearance": "The first human. Hebrew/ANE depictions and textual etymology (Hebrew adam → adamah, 'ground') describe the first man as formed from the brown earth — consistent with the Afro-Asiatic Semitic appearance of the original humans of the ANE.", "diet": "Originally vegetarian — every herb and fruit (Gen 1:29). After the Fall, ate the herb of the field by the sweat of his face (Gen 3:18-19).", "notable": "The original federal head of humanity. Paul calls Christ 'the last Adam' (1 Cor 15:45) — the second federal head who undoes what the first one did. 'As in Adam all die, even so in Christ shall all be made alive.'", "sources": "Genesis 2-5; 1 Chronicles 1:1; Luke 3:38; Romans 5:12-21; 1 Corinthians 15:22, 45; 1 Timothy 2:13-14; Strong's H121."},
  "Eve": {"altName": "Chavvah (Hebrew) — 'living/life-giver'", "biblical": "The first woman, formed from Adam's rib (Gen 2:21-22). Called 'the mother of all living' (Gen 3:20). Deceived by the serpent into eating the forbidden fruit. Mother of Cain, Abel, Seth, and other sons and daughters.", "region": "Eden, then east of Eden after the Fall.", "appearance": "The first woman, formed from Adam — same Afro-Asiatic Semitic features as her husband.", "diet": "Vegetarian in Eden; mixed diet after the Fall.", "notable": "The serpent told her 'ye shall be as gods' (Gen 3:5) — the first lie, repeating itself throughout history. Paul writes 'the woman being deceived was in the transgression' (1 Tim 2:14). Yet through her seed (Gen 3:15), the Messiah would come.", "sources": "Genesis 2-4; 2 Corinthians 11:3; 1 Timothy 2:13-14; Strong's H2332."},
  "Noah": {"altName": "Noach (Hebrew) — 'rest/comfort'", "biblical": "Tenth from Adam through Seth. 'A just man and perfect in his generations' (Gen 6:9). Walked with God. Built the ark over 100+ years and saved his family and the animals through the global Flood. Father of Shem, Ham, and Japheth — the three patriarchs of all nations after the Flood (Gen 10).", "region": "Before the Flood: somewhere in the antediluvian world. After: the ark came to rest on the mountains of Ararat (modern eastern Turkey/Armenia).", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic patriarch. Lived 950 years total. Genesis specifies he was 600 years old when the Flood came.", "diet": "Before the Flood: vegetarian by original Edenic command. After the Flood: God permitted meat — 'every moving thing that liveth shall be meat for you' (Gen 9:3).", "notable": "Saved through faith (Heb 11:7). Built an altar after the Flood — God established the Noahide covenant with all flesh (Gen 9). The rainbow is the covenant sign. Jesus called the days of Noah a type of his coming (Matt 24:37).", "sources": "Genesis 5-10; 1 Chronicles 1:4; Ezekiel 14:14, 20; Matthew 24:37-39; Luke 17:26-27; Hebrews 11:7; 1 Peter 3:20; 2 Peter 2:5; Strong's H5146."},
  "Cain": {"altName": "Qayin (Hebrew) — 'acquisition'", "biblical": "First son of Adam and Eve. Tiller of the ground. His offering was rejected; his brother Abel's was accepted. In jealousy he murdered Abel — the first murder. Marked by God and sent east of Eden to the land of Nod. Founder of the first named city, Enoch (named for his son, not the prophet).", "region": "Born in the world east of Eden; settled in Nod after the murder.", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic — first generation human.", "diet": "Farmer's diet — grains, fruits, vegetables.", "notable": "The Bible holds him up as the negative example: 'Not as Cain, who was of that wicked one, and slew his brother' (1 John 3:12). Cain's line is detailed in Genesis 4 — the first city-builders, polygamists, musicians, and metalworkers.", "sources": "Genesis 4; Hebrews 11:4; 1 John 3:12; Jude 11; Strong's H7014."},
  "Abel": {"altName": "Hevel (Hebrew) — 'breath/vapor' (same root as Ecclesiastes' 'vanity')", "biblical": "Second son of Adam and Eve. Keeper of sheep. Offered the firstlings of his flock — God accepted his offering. Murdered by his jealous brother Cain — the first murder, the first martyr.", "region": "Born east of Eden.", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic. Young man at his death.", "diet": "Shepherd's diet — milk, cheese, occasional meat.", "notable": "Jesus called him 'righteous Abel' (Matt 23:35) and the first prophet whose blood was shed. Hebrews 11:4 — 'By faith Abel offered unto God a more excellent sacrifice than Cain.' Hebrews 12:24 — 'the blood of sprinkling, that speaketh better things than that of Abel' (Christ's blood says 'forgive' where Abel's said 'avenge').", "sources": "Genesis 4; Matthew 23:35; Luke 11:51; Hebrews 11:4, 12:24; 1 John 3:12; Strong's H1893."},
  "Enoch": {"altName": "Chanok (Hebrew) — 'dedicated/initiated'", "biblical": "Seventh from Adam through Seth. 'Walked with God: and he was not; for God took him' (Gen 5:24) — translated to heaven without dying. Father of Methuselah (longest-lived man). Author of the prophecies preserved in 1 Enoch.", "region": "Antediluvian world.", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic patriarch. Lived 365 years on earth before translation.", "diet": "Antediluvian vegetarian diet.", "notable": "Hebrews 11:5 — 'By faith Enoch was translated that he should not see death.' Jude 14 quotes 1 Enoch directly: 'Behold, the Lord cometh with ten thousands of his saints.' One of two figures in the Bible (with Elijah) who did not die. Possibly returns as one of the Two Witnesses of Revelation 11.", "sources": "Genesis 5:18-24; 1 Chronicles 1:3; Luke 3:37; Hebrews 11:5; Jude 14-15; 1 Enoch (entire); Strong's H2585."},
  "Sarah": {"altName": "Sarai → Sarah (Hebrew) — 'princess'", "biblical": "Wife of Abraham. Mother of Isaac at age 90, after a lifetime of barrenness. Renamed by God from Sarai to Sarah at age 89. Buried in the cave of Machpelah (Gen 23) — the patriarchal tomb.", "region": "Born in Ur. Followed Abraham to Canaan. Lived in Hebron.", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic woman. Described as 'a fair woman to look upon' (Gen 12:11) — beautiful enough at 65 that Abraham feared Pharaoh would take her.", "diet": "Pastoralist diet — milk, cheese, dates, bread, occasional meat from her flocks.", "notable": "Mother of the promise (Gal 4:23). Laughed when told she'd bear a child (Gen 18:12) — and named Isaac ('he laughs') in honor of God's faithfulness. 1 Peter 3:6 holds her up as an example of holy women — 'whose daughters ye are.'", "sources": "Genesis 11-23; Isaiah 51:2; Romans 4:19, 9:9; Galatians 4:21-31; Hebrews 11:11; 1 Peter 3:6; Strong's H8283."},
  "Isaac": {"altName": "Yitzchaq (Hebrew) — 'he laughs'", "biblical": "Son of Abraham and Sarah, born when they were 100 and 90 (Gen 21:5). The child of promise. Nearly sacrificed by Abraham on Mount Moriah (Gen 22) — the great Akedah. Married Rebekah. Father of Jacob and Esau. Died at 180.", "region": "Born in Canaan; lived primarily in Beersheba and the Negev.", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic patriarch. Went blind in old age (Gen 27:1).", "diet": "Pastoral patriarch's diet. Loved venison — which Esau hunted for him.", "notable": "The only Genesis patriarch who never left the Promised Land. A type of Christ — the only son of the father, willingly bound, carrying the wood of his own sacrifice up the same mountain range where Jesus would die 2,000 years later.", "sources": "Genesis 17-35; Romans 9:7-9; Galatians 4:28; Hebrews 11:9, 17-20; Strong's H3327."},
  "Jacob": {"altName": "Yaaqov (Hebrew) — 'supplanter/heel-grabber' → renamed Israel ('struggles with God')", "biblical": "Younger twin of Esau. Bought the birthright with lentil stew. Stole Esau's blessing through deception. Fled to Haran. Worked 14 years for Rachel. Wrestled God at Jabbok and was renamed Israel. Father of the 12 sons who became the 12 tribes of Israel. Died in Egypt at 147.", "region": "Born in Canaan; fled to Haran for 20 years; returned to Canaan; died in Egypt.", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic patriarch. Walked with a limp after wrestling God at Jabbok (Gen 32:25). His mother Rebekah said he was 'a smooth man' (Gen 27:11) — contrasted with hairy Esau.", "diet": "Pastoralist patriarch's diet. Famous for the lentil stew he made.", "notable": "Father of the 12 tribes of Israel. His name 'Israel' is the name God's people bear forever. The story of his transformation from deceiver to wounded patriarch is one of the great character arcs in scripture.", "sources": "Genesis 25-50; Hosea 12:2-4; Matthew 1:2; Romans 9:13; Hebrews 11:9, 20-21; Strong's H3290."},
  "Esau": {"altName": "Esau (Hebrew) — 'hairy'; also called Edom ('red')", "biblical": "Older twin of Jacob (Gen 25:25). Hunter. Sold his birthright for lentil stew (Gen 25:34). Married Hittite and Canaanite women. Father of the Edomites — Israel's perpetual neighbor and antagonist.", "region": "Born in Canaan; settled in Mount Seir (Edom) southeast of the Dead Sea.", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic. Genesis emphasizes his hairiness and 'red' complexion at birth — earning him the name Edom.", "diet": "Hunter — venison was his specialty.", "notable": "Hebrews 12:16-17 calls him 'profane' because he sold his birthright. Yet Esau's reconciliation with Jacob (Gen 33:4) is one of scripture's most moving moments. His descendants (the Edomites) include Herod the Great.", "sources": "Genesis 25-36; Malachi 1:2-3; Romans 9:13; Hebrews 11:20, 12:16-17; Strong's H6215."},
  "Methuselah": {"altName": "Methushelach (Hebrew) — 'when he dies, it shall be sent' (the Flood)", "biblical": "Son of Enoch, grandfather of Noah. Lived 969 years — longest recorded human lifespan. Died the year of the Flood.", "region": "Antediluvian patriarch.", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic antediluvian patriarch.", "diet": "Antediluvian vegetarian.", "notable": "His name is a prophecy: 'when he dies, it shall be sent' — God's mercy kept him alive nearly a thousand years, but the Flood came the year he died.", "sources": "Genesis 5:21-27; 1 Chronicles 1:3; Luke 3:37; Strong's H4968."},
  "Seth": {"altName": "Sheth (Hebrew) — 'appointed/substituted'", "biblical": "Third son of Adam and Eve, born after Abel's death (Gen 4:25). Father of Enos. Through his line came Noah and Abraham and ultimately the Messiah (Luke 3:38).", "region": "Antediluvian.", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic, first-generation patriarch.", "diet": "Edenic-era vegetarian.", "notable": "Through Seth's line 'men began to call upon the name of the LORD' (Gen 4:26). Jesus' genealogy in Luke traces back through Seth to Adam to God.", "sources": "Genesis 4:25-5:8; 1 Chronicles 1:1; Luke 3:38; Strong's H8352."},
  "Lot": {"altName": "Lot (Hebrew) — 'covering/veil'", "biblical": "Abraham's nephew. Traveled with him from Ur to Canaan. Chose the well-watered Jordan plain — including Sodom. Rescued by Abraham after the battle of the kings (Gen 14). Lost his wife in the destruction of Sodom (Gen 19) — she looked back and became a pillar of salt. Father (by his daughters) of the Moabites and Ammonites.", "region": "Lived in Sodom; fled to the mountain caves above Zoar.", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic. Wealthy patriarch in his prime.", "diet": "Urban Sodomite fare in his prime; refugee in caves at the end.", "notable": "2 Peter 2:7 calls him 'just Lot' who was 'vexed with the filthy conversation of the wicked.' A righteous but compromised man whose choice of Sodom cost him his wife, his sons-in-law, his sons, his daughters' purity, and almost his life.", "sources": "Genesis 11-14, 19; Deuteronomy 2:9, 19; 2 Peter 2:7-8; Strong's H3876."},
  "Pharaoh": {"altName": "Title (not name) — Egyptian 'per-aa', 'great house'. The Bible uses it as a title for the kings of Egypt.", "biblical": "Multiple Pharaohs across the Bible. The most famous: (1) the Pharaoh of Joseph's elevation (Gen 41); (2) the 'Pharaoh which knew not Joseph' (Exod 1:8) who enslaved Israel; (3) the Pharaoh of the Exodus (Exod 5-14) whose heart was hardened through the ten plagues; (4) the Pharaoh contemporary with Solomon who gave his daughter as wife (1 Kgs 3:1).", "region": "Egypt — sometimes in Memphis, sometimes in Thebes, sometimes Pi-Ramesses.", "appearance": "Egyptian — North African, dark-skinned. The Pharaohs of the New Kingdom (closest to the Exodus) typically depicted with the double crown, false beard, and royal kilt.", "diet": "The royal table of Egypt — bread, beer, wine, beef, fish, fowl, fruit. Extravagant by any era's standards.", "notable": "God said to the Exodus Pharaoh: 'For this cause have I raised thee up, for to shew in thee my power' (Exod 9:16, quoted in Rom 9:17). The hardening of Pharaoh's heart is one of the most debated theological passages — God hardens (Exod 4:21, 7:3) AND Pharaoh hardens his own heart (Exod 8:15, 8:32, 9:34).", "sources": "Genesis 12, 37-50; Exodus 1-14; 1 Kings 3, 7, 9, 11; Isaiah 19; Romans 9:17; Hebrews 11:24; Strong's H6547."},
  "Nebuchadnezzar": {"altName": "Nebuchadrezzar (Aramaic spelling closer to original Akkadian 'Nabu-kudurri-usur', 'Nabu protect the heir')", "biblical": "King of Babylon ~605-562 BC. Destroyed Solomon's Temple in 586 BC. Carried Judah into exile in three waves (605, 597, 586 BC). Had the dream of the great statue (Dan 2). Made the golden image (Dan 3). Driven mad for seven years and ate grass like an ox (Dan 4). Restored to sanity and to the throne — confessed God's sovereignty.", "region": "Babylon (modern central Iraq). Ruled the largest empire in the world.", "appearance": "Mesopotamian/Akkadian. Royal Babylonian regalia: long curly beard, conical crown, fringed robes — known from countless Mesopotamian reliefs.", "diet": "The wealthiest royal table in the ancient world.", "notable": "The 'head of gold' in Daniel 2's statue. Builder of the Hanging Gardens (one of the Seven Wonders). The 'Nebuchadnezzar Chronicle' tablet (in the British Museum) confirms his 597 BC capture of Jerusalem to the exact day.", "sources": "2 Kings 24-25; 2 Chronicles 36; Jeremiah 21-52; Daniel 1-4; Strong's H5019."},
  "Cyrus": {"altName": "Kuroush (Persian) — Cyrus the Great", "biblical": "Founder of the Persian Empire (~559-530 BC). Conquered Babylon in 539 BC. Issued the decree allowing the Jews to return to Jerusalem and rebuild the Temple (Ezra 1:1-4, 2 Chr 36:22-23). Called by name in Isaiah 44:28 — written 150+ years before he was born.", "region": "Founded the Persian Empire from his Median/Persian homeland (modern Iran).", "appearance": "Indo-European Persian — distinct from the Semitic/Mesopotamian populations he conquered. Royal Persian regalia.", "diet": "Royal Persian table.", "notable": "God called him 'my shepherd' and 'his anointed' (Isa 44:28, 45:1) — the only non-Israelite called 'messiah/anointed' in scripture. The Cyrus Cylinder (in the British Museum) records his policy of returning exiled peoples to their homelands — independent confirmation of his Biblical decree.", "sources": "2 Chronicles 36:22-23; Ezra 1, 3-6; Isaiah 44:28, 45:1-13; Daniel 1:21, 6:28, 10:1; Strong's H3566."},
  "Mordecai": {"altName": "Mordecai (Hebrew, possibly Persian-influenced 'devotee of Marduk')", "biblical": "Cousin and adoptive father of Esther. Servant of the king at Shushan. Uncovered a plot to assassinate King Ahasuerus. Refused to bow to Haman — Haman plotted to destroy all Jews. Through Esther's intervention, the plot was reversed and Mordecai was elevated to second only to the king.", "region": "Shushan (Susa), capital of the Persian Empire.", "appearance": "Jewish exile in Persian dress.", "diet": "Royal court fare.", "notable": "His name lives on in the Feast of Purim — Israel's annual celebration of the Esther deliverance.", "sources": "Esther 2-10; Strong's H4782."},
  "Ezra": {"altName": "Ezra (Hebrew) — 'help'", "biblical": "Priest and scribe of the law of Moses. Led the second wave of exiles back to Jerusalem ~458 BC. Reformed Israel's religious life. Read the law aloud to the assembled people (Neh 8) — possibly compiled and edited the Hebrew canon as we know it.", "region": "Babylon, then Jerusalem.", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic Jewish priest.", "diet": "Priestly diet.", "notable": "Ezra 7:10 — 'Ezra had prepared his heart to seek the law of the LORD, and to do it, and to teach in Israel statutes and judgments.' The model of a Bible teacher.", "sources": "Ezra 7-10; Nehemiah 8, 12; Strong's H5830."},
  "Nehemiah": {"altName": "Nechemyah (Hebrew) — 'comforted of YHWH'", "biblical": "Cupbearer to King Artaxerxes I of Persia. Heard of Jerusalem's broken walls and wept. Sent by the king with letters and provisions. Rebuilt the walls in 52 days despite opposition from Sanballat and Tobiah.", "region": "Shushan, then Jerusalem.", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic Jew serving in Persian court dress.", "diet": "Persian court fare in exile; modest Jerusalem fare during reconstruction.", "notable": "Outstanding leader and intercessor. Repeatedly cried 'Remember me, O my God' (Neh 5:19, 13:14, 13:22, 13:31). The model of prayer-driven action.", "sources": "Nehemiah 1-13; Strong's H5166."},
  "Andrew": {"altName": "Andreas (Greek) — 'manly'", "biblical": "Fisherman of Bethsaida. Brother of Simon Peter. One of the first two disciples called (with John, from John the Baptist's circle). Brought his brother Peter to Jesus (John 1:40-42). Found the boy with the five loaves and two fish (John 6:8-9).", "region": "Bethsaida and Capernaum on the Sea of Galilee; tradition says he later preached in Scythia (Russia/Ukraine) and was martyred on an X-shaped cross in Patras, Greece.", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic Galilean fisherman.", "diet": "Fisherman's diet.", "notable": "The first disciple. Often the 'bringer' — bringing Peter, bringing the boy with the loaves, bringing the Greeks to Jesus (John 12:20-22).", "sources": "Matthew 4, 10; Mark 1, 3, 13; Luke 6; John 1, 6, 12; Acts 1; Strong's G406."},
  "James": {"altName": "Yaakov (Hebrew) → Iakobos (Greek) — same name as 'Jacob' in English", "biblical": "Two important apostles named James: (1) James son of Zebedee, brother of John, one of the inner three (Peter, James, John). First apostle martyred — killed by Herod Agrippa I (Acts 12:2). (2) James the Lord's brother, leader of the Jerusalem church, author of the Epistle of James, martyred by stoning ~AD 62 (per Josephus Antiquities XX.9).", "region": "(1) Galilean fisherman. (2) Jerusalem.", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic Jew.", "diet": "(1) Galilean fisherman's diet. (2) Jerusalem ascetic — Hegesippus records James the Just took the Nazirite vow.", "notable": "James the Lord's brother presided over the Jerusalem Council (Acts 15). His epistle is one of the most practical books in the NT. Confirmed historically by Josephus's mention of his stoning.", "sources": "Mark 6:3; Acts 12, 15, 21; 1 Corinthians 15:7; Galatians 1:19, 2:9; James 1-5; Josephus Antiquities XX.9; Strong's G2385."},
  "John": {"altName": "Yochanan (Hebrew) → Ioannes (Greek) — 'YHWH is gracious'", "biblical": "Son of Zebedee, brother of James. One of the inner three. 'The disciple whom Jesus loved.' Author of the Gospel of John, three epistles, and Revelation. Mary entrusted to him at the cross (John 19:26-27). Exiled to Patmos under Domitian. Tradition: died in Ephesus around AD 100 — the only apostle not martyred.", "region": "Galilean fisherman; later Ephesus; exiled to Patmos.", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic Jewish fisherman. Lived the longest of any apostle.", "diet": "Galilean fare; in old age, lived in Ephesus.", "notable": "The only NT author called 'the theologian.' Wrote the deepest Gospel ('In the beginning was the Word') and the final book of the Bible. The longest-lived eyewitness of Jesus.", "sources": "All four Gospels; Acts 3-4; Galatians 2:9; 1-3 John; Revelation; Strong's G2491."},
  "Matthew": {"altName": "Matthias/Levi (Hebrew origin) → Mattheos (Greek) — 'gift of YHWH'", "biblical": "Tax collector (publican) at Capernaum. Called by Jesus from his tax booth (Matt 9:9). Held a feast in his house where Jesus dined with 'publicans and sinners.' Wrote the Gospel of Matthew — the most Jewish of the four Gospels.", "region": "Capernaum; tradition says he preached in Ethiopia or Parthia.", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic Jew working for Rome.", "diet": "Wealthy publican's fare.", "notable": "The hated tax collector becomes the writer of the Bible's most quoted Gospel. Lists himself as 'Matthew the publican' in his apostle list (10:3) — others just say 'Matthew.' Humility.", "sources": "Matthew 9-10; Mark 2-3; Luke 5-6; Acts 1; Strong's G3156."},
  "Mary_Magdalene": {"altName": "Miryam of Magdala — same name as Jesus' mother and Miriam Moses' sister", "biblical": "Woman from Magdala in Galilee. Jesus cast seven demons out of her (Mark 16:9, Luke 8:2). Followed Jesus and supported his ministry from her own means. Present at the Cross. First witness of the resurrection (Mark 16:9, John 20:11-18).", "region": "Magdala on the western shore of the Sea of Galilee; followed Jesus to Jerusalem.", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic Jewish woman.", "diet": "Galilean Jewish diet.", "notable": "The FIRST witness of the resurrection. Jesus spoke her name — 'Mary' — and she recognized him (John 20:16). Despite first-century rejection of women's testimony, all four Gospels name her as the first witness.", "sources": "Matthew 27-28; Mark 15-16; Luke 8, 24; John 19-20; Strong's G3094."},
  "Stephen": {"altName": "Stephanos (Greek) — 'crown'", "biblical": "One of the seven chosen to serve the Hellenist widows (Acts 6). 'A man full of faith and of the Holy Ghost.' Performed great wonders. His sermon before the Sanhedrin (Acts 7) is the longest in Acts. Saw Jesus standing at God's right hand. The first Christian martyr — stoned with Saul (Paul) watching the coats.", "region": "Jerusalem.", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic Hellenistic Jew.", "diet": "Jerusalem Hellenistic Jewish fare.", "notable": "His martyrdom directly precipitated Paul's conversion. Stephen's prayer 'Lord, lay not this sin to their charge' (Acts 7:60) echoes Christ's 'Father, forgive them.' Saul (Paul) likely never forgot.", "sources": "Acts 6-8; Strong's G4736."},
  "Barnabas": {"altName": "Joses → Barnabas (Aramaic) — 'son of consolation/encouragement'", "biblical": "Levite from Cyprus. Sold his land and gave to the apostles (Acts 4:36-37). Vouched for Saul (Paul) when no one would (Acts 9:27). Sent to Antioch to oversee the first Gentile church. Brought Paul to Antioch. Companion on Paul's first missionary journey. Later separated from Paul over Mark — and the parting led to two missionary teams instead of one.", "region": "Cyprus; Jerusalem; Antioch; first missionary journey.", "appearance": "Afro-Asiatic Semitic Cypriot Jew.", "diet": "Diaspora Jewish fare.", "notable": "Called 'a good man' (Acts 11:24) — a rare biblical description. The encourager who validated Paul and Mark when others wouldn't. Tradition holds he was martyred on Cyprus around AD 61.", "sources": "Acts 4, 9, 11-15; 1 Corinthians 9:6; Galatians 2:1-13; Colossians 4:10; Strong's G921."}
};
